We found that the reason there are so many missing varibles invloving the garage are missing is because these houses don't have a garage. So we will fill in these variables with "none" so they are no longer counted as "missing".

#Filling in the missing Garage data
data_imputed = data.copy()

numeric_columns = ['GarageType', 'GarageYrBlt','GarageQual', 'GarageCond', 'GarageFinish']

for col in numeric_columns:
  if data_imputed[col].isnull().any():
    data_imputed[col] = data_imputed[col].fillna('None')

#Filling in the missing data points for the houses that don't have a basement
numeric_columns_basement = ['BsmtQual', 'BsmtCond', 'BsmtExposure', 'BsmtFinType1', 'BsmtFinType2']

for col in numeric_columns_basement:
  mask = (data_imputed[col].isnull()) & (data_imputed['TotalBsmtSF'] == 0)
  data_imputed.loc[mask, col] = data_imputed.loc[mask, col].fillna('None')

Part 2

Creating new features in our housing dataset

#Total Sqaure foot of all the porchs combined
data_clean['TotalPorchSF'] = data_clean['OpenPorchSF'] + data_clean['EnclosedPorch'] + data_clean['3SsnPorch'] + data_clean['ScreenPorch'] + data_clean['WoodDeckSF']

#Having a feature contain the houses total Sqaure Footage
data_clean['TotalSF'] = data_clean['TotalPorchSF'] + data_clean['TotalBsmtSF'] + data_clean['1stFlrSF'] + data_clean['2ndFlrSF'] + data_clean['GarageArea'] + data_clean['PoolArea'] + data_clean['GrLivArea']

#Price of house per sqaure foot
data_clean['PricePerSF'] = data_clean['SalePrice'] / data_clean['TotalSF']

#Garage
# 1: yes garage, 0: no garage
data_clean['Garage'] = (data_clean['GarageArea'] > 0).astype(int)

#Basement
# 1: yes basement, 0: no basement
data_clean['Bsmt'] = (data_clean['TotalBsmtSF'] > 0).astype(int)

#Pool
# 1: yes pool, 0: no pool
data_clean['Pool'] = (data_clean['PoolArea'] > 0).astype(int)

#Fireplace
# 1: yes fireplace, 0: no fireplace
data_clean['FireplaceThere'] = (data_clean['Fireplaces'] > 0).astype(int)

#Miscellaneous Feature
# 1: yes miscellaneous feature, 0: no miscellaneous feature
data_clean['MiscFeatureThere'] = (data_clean['MiscVal'] > 0).astype(int)

  sale price increase by -1513.96,
  HOLDING OTHER HOUSING FEATURES CONSTANT.

TotalSF: 58148.59
  When TotalSF increases by 1 standard deviation,
  sale price increase by 58148.59,
  HOLDING OTHER HOUSING FEATURES CONSTANT.

PricePerSF: 43023.64
  When PricePerSF increases by 1 standard deviation,
  sale price increase by 43023.64,
  HOLDING OTHER HOUSING FEATURES CONSTANT.

TotalPorchSF: -24.62
  When TotalPorchSF increases by 1 standard deviation,
  sale price increase by -24.62,
  HOLDING OTHER HOUSING FEATURES CONSTANT.

After making our model and interpreting our coefficants, we can see when it comes to our "luxury" features that a garage could actually hurt the selling price of a house, and if it is there the larger the area the more valuable it becomes. The basement being apart of the house can increase it's selling price while wether it contains bathrooms could hurt it. The pool can hurt the selling price if it isn't there while the area of the pool can increase the price. Fireplaces can also hurt the price if not there and the number of them can increase price. Miscellaneous features can help the price if there while their value could potenionally hurt the price.

At the end of the day "luxury" feature can hurt or help a house's selling price but they don't carry as much weight as a feature like total square footage does when determining a house's selling price.

Evaluating our Multivariate Regression Model

# Make predictions on training set
y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_scaled)

# Calculating metrics
r2_train = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
mse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
rmse_train = np.sqrt(mse_train)

print("Training Set Performance:")
print(f"  R-squared: {r2_train:.4f}")
print(f"  MSE: {mse_train:.4f}")
print(f"  RMSE: {rmse_train:.4f}")

Training Set Performance:
  R-squared: 0.9625
  MSE: 244337301.5797
  RMSE: 15631.2924

# Make predictions on test set
y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

# Calculating metrics
r2_test = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
mse_test = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
rmse_test = np.sqrt(mse_test)

print("Test Set Performance:")
print(f"  R-squared: {r2_test:.4f}")
print(f"  MSE: {mse_test:.4f}")
print(f"  RMSE: {rmse_test:.4f}")

Test Set Performance:
  R-squared: 0.8345
  MSE: 913048087.8662
  RMSE: 30216.6856

# Compare metrics
comparison = pd.DataFrame({
    'Metric': ['R-squared', 'MSE', 'RMSE'],
    'Training': [r2_train, mse_train, rmse_train],
    'Test': [r2_test, mse_test, rmse_test]
})

print(comparison)

When comparing our trainging and testing sets we can see that our R-squares aren't very different. While our RMSE has more of a difference. And our MSE has a huge difference between training and testing set.

# Plot actual vs predicted values for test set
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test, y_test_pred, alpha=0.6)
plt.plot([y_test.min(), y_test.max()], [y_test.min(), y_test.max()], 'r--', lw=2)
plt.xlabel('Actual Sale Price')
plt.ylabel('Predicted Sale Price')
plt.title('Actual vs Predicted Sale Price (Test Set)')
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plot residuals (prediction errors)
residuals = y_test - y_test_pred

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test_pred, residuals, alpha=0.6)
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--', lw=2)
plt.xlabel('Predicted Sale Price')
plt.ylabel('Residuals (Actual - Predicted)')
plt.title('Residual Plot')
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

We can also see that our residual plot isn't exactly linear and is making a bit of an U shaped curve meaning that our model isn't exactly the best to be used when making these predictions.
